11. Prospectively, exercise general supervision over Barangays to ensure timely and efficient implementation of their projects;
12. In coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), identify and address the difficulties encountered in project implementation to avoid incurrence in the future;
13. Instruct the MPDC to closely monitor and track the implementation of the projects of the Municipality in accordance with the approved development plan, promptly informing the former of any deviations; and
14. Ensure that the Municipal Engineer implements the projects funded under LGSF-SBDP of the NTF-ELCAC within the prescribed timeline.

17. Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the Trust Fund books;
18. Proactively anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation; and
19. Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects throughout the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

22. Require the implementing unit to refrain from granting contract time extensions, for request made, without careful examination of facts that would justify an extension;
23. Provide PAGASA weather reports to substantiate any claims for time extensions or enforce liquidated damages from the supplier; and
24. Adhere strictly to the standards set forth in RA No. 9184 and its R-IRR, particularly on the approval of contract time extensions, and ensure proper evaluation of the conditions warranting such requests.

26. Require the BAC to strictly verify, validate and confirm the veracity, authenticity and validity of all documents submitted by the bidder using non-discretionary criteria;
27. Ensure that other necessary licenses and permits required by law are carefully check in accordance with Section 34.2 of 2016 R-IRR of RA No. 9184; and
28. Review the project’s costing in relation to market research conducted by the procuring entity and consider reduction of contract cost for the item that has been removed.

35. Monitor the status of transferred funds to identify unutilized balances of completed PPAs and comply with COA Circular No. 94-013 on the return of the unexpended balances on a timely manner;
36. Coordinate with other Department Heads to utilize the balances allocated to them and also coordinate with the BTr on how to return the unexpended balances with unidentified or closed SA; and
37. Ensure the accuracy of reported Due to NGAs accounts by ensuring these accounts exist as at year-end.

We recommended that LDRRMO:
Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the Trust Fund books;
Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM projects, programs and activities (PPAs) to avoid delays or non-implementation;
Maximize LDRRMF utilization focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management and consider the needs of the time, such as the COVID-19 emergency; and
Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Until such time when there is a dedicated General Service Officer or Supply Officer and optimal storage space, require the responsible official for timely liquidation of the inventories under their office;
Require the Inventory Committee of LGU-Mercedes to conduct physical inventory taking of Supplies Inventory semi-annually as required under the existing rules and regulations;
Require Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee to reconcile the Inventory Accounts per books with the actual supplies inventory at hand; and
Require the Municipal Accountant present fairly the Inventory Accounts in the Financial Statements as of year-end.

We recommended the Management, in strict compliance with rules set forth by RA No. 9184, to:

Be cautious in creation of advertisement in the Philippine Government Electronic Procurement System (PhilGEPS);
Avoid accepting eligibility requirements after the deadline of submission of bids;
Use non-discretionary pass/fail criteria especially during bid evaluation and/or opening of bids, and during post-qualification;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit suspension orders or any documents that would warrant the non-imposition of liquidated damages to the concerned contractor to the Office of the Municipal Accountant copy furnished the Audit Team, if any. Otherwise, direct the Municipal Accountant to compute the liquidated damages for the above-mentioned project;
Ensure that the winning bidder post the required performance securities upon entering into contract; and
Exert extra caution or close watch with the details of performance securities, surety bonds and other documents, particularly, its validity.

We recommended the Management take the following courses of action:

